# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-america
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-america/1961-ncaa-university-division-baseball-rankings] The following poll makes up the **1961 NCAA University Division baseball rankings.** Collegiate Baseball Newspaper published its first human poll of the top 20 teams in college baseball in 1957.
[src:baseball-america/1961-ncaa-university-division-baseball-rankings] The 1961 season was the first to rank the top 30 teams.
[src:baseball-america/1981-ncaa-division-i-baseball-rankings] The following polls make up the **1981 NCAA Division I baseball rankings.** Baseball America began publishing its poll of the top 20 teams in college baseball in 1981.
[src:baseball-america/1981-ncaa-division-i-baseball-rankings] Collegiate Baseball Newspaper published its first human poll of the top 20 teams in college baseball in 1957, and expanded to rank the top 30 teams in 1961.
[src:baseball-america/1981-ncaa-division-i-baseball-rankings] This was the first season with two major polls.
[src:baseball-america/1982-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1982 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-america/1983-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1983 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-america/1984-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1984 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-america/1985-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1985 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-america/1985-ncaa-division-i-baseball-rankings] The following polls make up the **1985 NCAA Division I baseball rankings.** Baseball America began publishing its poll of the top 20 teams in college baseball in 1981.
[src:baseball-america/1985-ncaa-division-i-baseball-rankings] Beginning with the 1985 season, it expanded to the top 25.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] Source Interlink (later the Motor Trend Group) purchased Baseball America in December 2011 and sold the publication in February 2017.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] The new Baseball America Enterprises includes Gary Green and Larry Botel of Alliance Baseball, owners of minor league franchises in Omaha, Nebraska, and Richmond, Virginia, in partnership with David Geaslen, founder and CEO of 3STEP Sports.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] Today, *Baseball America* is led by president Tom Dondero and Editor in Chief J.J.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] Other annual publications produced by the company include *Baseball America Almanac*, *Baseball America Prospect Handbook* (a *New York Times* sports best-seller in March 2016), and the *Baseball America Directory*.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] *Baseball America*also has an active social media presence on YouTube and Instagram.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] Note: Each year's team consists of a varying number of pitchers and types of pitchers.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] The "Organization of the Year" award was first presented in 1982.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] In addition to these awards, *Baseball America* releases rankings of the top 25 teams in the nation, as voted by its staff.
[src:baseball-america/baseball-america] A preseason poll is compiled, in addition to a weekly poll during the season.
